			<div class="postrow">
				
				
				<h2 class="title icon">
					Re: Making Sense of the Steelers' Linebacker Situation
				</h2>
				


						
						
				<div class="content">
					<div id="post_message_383434">
						<blockquote class="postcontent restore ">
							Excellent post. I personally think Timmons should switch to weak-side OLB as soon as the opportunity arises. I understand that he can't do that right now (with Harrison as DPOY) but I think he is much better suited to play outside for two reasons:<br />
<br />
1) All of those check down RB screen passes into the flat, and even WR screens/quick slants. That is where the great teams really like to attack us. Timmons has excellent closing speed which not only helps in stopping those plays for short yardage, but also prevents opposing OC's from calling them so many times per game. I realize the OLB is usually rushing the QB but there are times he can jump into coverage.<br />
<br />
2) Rushing the QB from the outside takes a different set of skills than blitzing from the inside. Timmons is fast enough to beat LT's. Let me repeat that... Timmons has the burst of speed necessary to beat starting LT's. You can't teach that. And you usually can't draft that in round two. Timmons problem is with the bull rush (which is where he often ends up playing ILB) so let's play to his strengths.  <br />
<br />
If Timmons was 'allowed' to play outside he would not be considered a disappointment at 1.15 he would be producing double digit sacks and chasing down RB's from behind.<br />
<br />
I think we should look to draft one more solid ILB and let Timmons shift outside if/when Harrison starts fading. Of course Graham would be a delicious luxury. I'd love to have him. It just doesn't make as much sense this year.
						</blockquote>
					</div>

					
				</div>
			</div>
			
